  "prompt": "Why does Locke decide to kill Bran Stark at Craster's Keep?",
  "response": "In the TV series *Game of Thrones*, Locke does not decide to kill Bran Stark at Craster's Keep; rather, he captures Bran and his companions with the intent of bringing him back to the Dreadfort to gain favor with Roose Bolton. Locke, a loyal bannerman of House Bolton, is acting under orders from Roose, who wants to eliminate any Stark heirs to solidify his control over the North.\n\nAt Craster's Keep, Locke and his men encounter Bran, Hodor, Meera, and Jojen, who are hiding in the aftermath of the mutiny at the keep. Locke recognizes Bran's identity and seizes him, but his plans are interrupted by Jon Snow and the Night's Watch, who arrive to deal with the mutineers at Craster's Keep. During the ensuing chaos, Locke attempts to escape with Bran but is ultimately killed by Jon Snow's direwolf, Ghost.\n\nSo, Locke's primary goal was not to kill Bran but to capture him for political reasons, leveraging him as a valuable asset for House Bolton. His death at Craster's Keep prevents him from carrying out this plan.",
